rong>Lesley Williams, Leyburn, Wensleydale (and her Mum) </strong></p>\n <p>Lesley, 44, is an active lady.Â  She works a fitness instructor and is mum to three children aged 9, 11 and 13.Â A couple of years ago, Lesley started to suffer from involuntary twitching in both her legs.Â  It came upon her whenever she was sitting still for a long while â€“ such as a long car journey or when at the cinema â€“ and at night as she tried to relax and sleep.</p>\n <p>Her involuntary leg twitching is more commonly known as Restless Legs Syndrome (RLS).Â  And while doctors accept it is a condition, there is little they know about it and less they can do about it.Â  Lesley\'s GP was baffled as to what to do.Â  Last Autumn Lesley read in a fitness magazine about a supplement called vitalMAX. The article suggested this product could help with Restless Legs Syndrome by increasing the level of dopamine â€“ a neurotransmitter in the brain that, among other things, is responsible for the co-ordination and control of movement.Â  Published research studies link low levels of dopamine with RLS.Â  </p>\n <p>Lesley was at her wits\' end so decided to give vitalMAX a try.Â  Within a month her RLS was significantly reduced.Â  </p>\n <p>Lesley\'s mother, 77, has suffered from RLS for nearly 10 years.Â  Her condition was more pronounced than Lesley\'s to the point where she started to worry and panic when sitting in confined spaces.Â  Long car journeys, a trip to the cinema and a leisurely meal were all out of the question.Â  Not to mention the fact she never slept well.Â  Again, her GP in Reading could offer no advice.Â  Having enjoyed the benefits of vitalMAX Lesley introduced her mum to it â€“ and her symptoms have cleared completely!Â  This has made a huge difference to her.Â  As an active grandma with three daughters and seven grandchildren, her life has been enhanced greatly by solving this problem.</p>\n <p>&quot;RLS is very uncomfortable and you can\'t control it at all,&quot; says Lesl