octors and patients should pay attention to.\n\nThis was the conclusion drawn from the study by Dr. Arshad Jahangir, a heart rhythm specialist at the Mayo Clinic Arizona in Scottsdale. He led the study and recently presented the results at an American College of Cardiology conference in New Orleans.\n\nRestless legs syndrome is thought to affect millions of people although some doctors think its seriousness has been exaggerated, possibly to help sell treatments. However it has long been known that other types of sleep disturbances such as sleep apnoea carry an accompanying higher risk of heart problems. This study is one of the first to look at how RLS may relate to other aspects of health.\n\nIt involved 584 people diagnosed with the syndrome by a neurologist based on four widely used criteria. Participants were given an imaging test that allowed heart thickness to be measured three ways, and were kept overnight so their sleep could be monitored. Afterward, researchers divided them into two groups based on the frequency of leg twitches. The 45% who twitched at least 35 times per hour were more likely to have the thick-heart condition than the other 55% of study participants who kicked less often. Looking at all study participants about three years later, researchers saw that those with severely thick hearts â€” about a quarter of the total group â€” were more than twice as likely to have suffered a heart problem or to have died.\n\nâ€œPeople with restless legs are advised not to panic, but rather discuss with their doctor whether more tests are needed to look for an enlarged heartâ€ Dr Jahangir said.\n\n<strong>Our comments:</strong>\n\nThe low dopamine that is associated with restless legs, may also lie behind thisÂ heart wallÂ thickening sinceÂ dopamine is necessary for adequate heart function.\n\n<strong>Our recommended product for RLS, vitalCALM</strong>, is also very beneficial for the heart and circulatory system. Not only do the enhanced dopamine levels help the circulatory system function better, theÂ high levels of resveratrol help protect the heart and blood vessels. Resveratrol isÂ the polyphenol at the centre of the \"French Paradox\" the theory which explains why the French can eat very high saturated fat diets but have a low rate of heart disease.\n\nKnown as the <strong>\"longevity molecule\"</strong>Â resveratrol:\n<ul>\n	<li>inhibitsÂ oxidative degradation of lipids, by scavenging free radicals</li>\n	<li>inhibits the polymerisation of beta-amyloidÂ helping to prevent cognitive decline/senility/Alzheimers</li>\n	<li>protectsÂ vascular tissue, such as collagen andÂ elastin, thoughtÂ to be responsible for its cardiovascular benefits</li>\n	<li>protects against osteoporosisÂ via the stimulation of osteoblasts, the cells responsible for bone formation, and by increasing bone mineralisation</li>\n</ul>','RLS sufferers may have hidden heart problems','','draft','open','closed','','rls-sufferers-may-have-hidden-heart-problems','','','2011-04-08 20:42:38','2011-04-08 19:42:38','',0,'http://www.simplyvital.com/blog/?p=607',0,'post','',0),(654,2,'2011-06-10 11:59:34','2011-06-10 10:59:34','<strong>Soy isoflavones significantly improve cognitive performance in postmenopausal women</strong>\n\nTwo studies by the research group of Prof. Louise Dye, Human Appetite Research Unit, the Institute of Psychological Sciences at the University of Leeds, demonstrate a statistically significant effect of the consumption of soy isoflavones on specific aspects of memory in postmenopausal women.\n\nIn 21 postmenopausal women, 100mg/d soy isoflavones taken for 8 weeks improved specific indices of verbal learning and memory after 4 weeks, and frontal lobe functioning after 8 weeks. Soy isoflavones were found to exert stronger cognitive effects in postmenopausal women compared to premenopausal women.Â  The physiological response to soy isoflavones may differ between postmenopausal and premenopausal women.Â  Circulating oestrogen was not significantly affected by soy isoflavones in the premenopausal women, but there was a significant increase in peripheral oestrogen in the postmenopausal women.\n\nIt is well established that endogenous oestrogen levels play an important role in cognition. Oestrogen levels are also linked with neurodegeneration with age and cognitive decline in postmenopausal women.\n\nFind soy isoflavones in <strong>vitalWOMAN</strong>','Soy isoflavones significantly improve cognitive performance','','publish','open','closed','','soy-isoflavones-improve-cognitive-performance','','','2011-06-10 11:59:34','2011-06-10 10:59:34','',0,'http://www.simplyvital.com/blog/?p=654',0,'post','',0),(657,2,'2011-06-10 12:02:43','2011-06-10 11:02:43','<strong>Why is skin cancer on the increase?</strong>\n\n<strong>Should we trust mother nature or put our faith in sunscreen?</strong>\n\n<strong>Our bodies have evolved under the sun and it has mechanisms to cope with limited exposure. Â We did not evolve with sunscreens, which encourage hours of continuous exposure.\n</strong>\nAustralia is known to have the world\'s highest rate of skin cancer per head of population (although recent figures suggest the UK is about to take the lead).Â  The cause is sunlight.Â  The sun\'s ultraviolet light wreaks havoc with the DNA in our skin cells, causing them to mutate and become cancerous. And those of us with fair Northern European skins have little natural protection.\n\nPublic health awareness campaigns over the last 20 years have encouraged us to use suncreams Â and to wear protective clothing, especially in peak periods in the middle of the day when we are in the sun.\n\nÂ However, we do need some exposure to sunlight as studies researching the association between levels of Â vitamin D and various diseases testifies. These studies reveal that there are widespread deficiencies in levels of vitamin D with lack of exposure to sunlight and sunbathing with sunscreens to blame.\n\nVitamin D is essential for a range of metabolic processes, particularly those concerned with bone metabolism - and almost all vitamin D comes from sunlight Â (a small amount comes from the diet, but not enough to keep us healthy). And although in most cases the deficiencies are mild, they\'re enough to concern experts working in the field of bone metabolism and bone disease.\n\nGroups most at risk are:\n<ul>\n	<li>Those in colder climes, especially those who work and/or spend a lot of time indoors (especially those living in high-rise apartments without gardens). Many of these people leave for work early in the morning, get home after dark, and don\'t get much sunlight.</li>\n	<li>Children who spend long periods in front of computers and don\'t go outdoors.</li>\n	<li>Dark-skinned immigrants from Africa, India and Pakistan; these people have increased amounts of melanin pigment in the skin that blocks UV light from sunlight, so their bodies don\'t make as much vitamin D as fair-skinned people.</li>\n	<li>People who cover up most of their body - for example Islamic women who wear the veil.</li>\n</ul>\nThose with the highest risk of all are the elderly who are immobile and stay indoors, particularly those in nursing homes and other aged care facilities.\n\nAccording to an editorial in the latest Medical Journal of Australia (where we know they have more sun than most!), nearly a third of men and women have mild to moderate vitamin D deficiency. Almost half of nursing home patients have at least mild Vitamin D deficiency.\n\n<strong>Low levels of Vitamin D can cause:</strong>\n\n-Rickets - a childhood disease in which the bones soften and can become misshapen (in adults the condition is called osteomalacia).\n\n-Osteoporosis - thinning of the bones. Osteoporosis is a major risk factor for hip fractures, especially in the elderly.\n\n-There\'s also evidence that low levels of vitamin D predispose to some cancers - especially cancer of the breast, colon and prostate.\n\nSo how do we keep our vitamin D levels up?Â  A few foods contain vitamin D - notably, fish with a high fat content Â (like sardines, salmon, herring and mackerel), meat and eggs. Some milk and milk products - powdered milk, yoghurts and cheeses - are fortified with vitamin D.Â  But these foods aren\'t nearly enough to give us adequate vitamin D, according to the experts.\n\n<strong>We need to spend some time in the sun without sunscreens!</strong>\n\nIn March 2006, a group consisting of The Working Group of the Australian and New Zealand Bone and Mineral Society, the Endocrine Society of Australia and Osteoporosis Australia published a position statement in the Medical Journal of Australia. They recommended that people need certain minimal levels of sunlight to get adequate vitamin D levels.Â  If they\'re at risk of having lower-than-normal levels of vitamin D, they need to increase their sun exposure.\n\n<strong>Skin doctors alarmed..so who\'s right?</strong><strong></strong>\n\nThe Australasian College of Dermatologists is concerned about suggestions that people get more sunlight.Â Â  \"Almost all Australians will have enough exposure to the sun to get adequate levels of Vitamin D, simply by being outdoors for short periods of time,\" says Dr Stephen Shumack, the College\'s Honorary Secretary.Â  \"There\'s no evidence that people who have mildly lower levels of Vitamin D are going to get bone disease. The connection hasn\'t been proved,\" he says.\n\nHe says, â€œYes, in some cases, people institutionalised in nursing homes have sub-optimal levels of vitamin D.Â  They need to be treated with vitamin D supplements.Â  But to advise healthy Australians to get additional sunlight is potentially dangerous, he argues.\n\n<strong>Avoiding skin cancer risk</strong><strong></strong>\n\nProfessor Rebecca Mason, an expert on vitamin D and calcium metabolism and Professor of Physiology at the University of Sydney, says the recommended levels of sunlight exposure will not put anyone at risk of skin cancer.Â  Those levels are:\n\n-Â Â Â Â  in summer, six to eight minutes a day on most days (that\'s about 10-15 minutes in northern Europe)\n\n-Â Â Â Â  in winter, half an hour most days (make it 1 hour for us!)\n\nYou need to have only 15 per cent of your body exposed - arms, hands and face - to get this exposure. She agrees that most people will already get this amount.Â  But those people in the at-risk group should make sure they get at least this amount.Â  People with dark skin may need more.Â  We need to maintain a balance - we need enough sunlight to keep our bones healthy but not so much that we\'re at risk of skin cancer.\n\n<strong>Precisely!</strong>\n\n<strong>And the problem with suncreams</strong>\n\nis that they encourage over-exposure to the damaging rays of the sun while preventing the good rays from stimulating vitamin D production. The bottom line is that the data shows that those who use suncreams have a higher incidence of skin cancers!\n\n<strong>The golden rules are:</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li>start exposing your skin slowly to the sun, 10mins max on day one, 15 the next etc</li>\n	<li>avoid the sun during 11-3pm</li>\n	<li>do not allow yourself to burn</li>\n	<li>protect young skins well with hats etc as children are more vulnerable to burning and evidence links burning in childhood with skin problems later</li>\n	<li>eat lots of carotenoids i.e coloured fruits and veg....see vitalLIFE</li>\n	<li>drink tea as it contains protective molecules too</li>\n</ul>','The suncream debate...','','draft','open','closed','','the-suncream-debate','','','2011-06-10 12:02:43','2011-06-10 11:02:43','',0,'http://www.simplyvital.com/blog/?p=657',0,'post','',0),(659,2,'2010-06-10 12:03:58','2010-06-10 11:03:58','<strong>All men need to look after their prostate gland and improving theÂ omega-3 to omega-6 ratio in the diet mayÂ cut prostate cancer risk\n</strong>\n<strong>Over half a million news cases of prostate cancer are diagnosed every year world wide, and the cancer is the direct cause of over 200,000 deaths.</strong>\n\nThe incidence of the disease is also increasing with a rise of 1.7 per cent over 15 years.\n\nHowever a new study lead by researcher Professor William Aronson at the David Geffen School of Medicine at UCLA, adds to a growing body of evidence linking an increased <a href=\"javascript:KeywordSearch(\'KEYWORDS=omega-3&amp;period=all&amp;inner=1\');\">omega-3</a> to omega-6 intake ratio to improved health and <strong>prevention of prostate cancer </strong>can now be added to that list.\n\nEarlier this year, researchers from the Paterson Institute, a cancer research institute funded by British charity Cancer Research UK and affiliated with the University of Manchester reported that omega 6 fats increased the spread of prostate tumour cells into bone marrow, while omega-3 fatty acids were seen to block this invasion (British Journal of Cancer, doi: 10.1038/sj.bjc.6603030).Â  This new research, published in the new issue of the journal Clinical Cancer Research (Vol. 12, Issue 15), suggests that changing the ration of omega-3 to omega-6 in the typical Western diet might reduce prostate cancer tumor growth rates and PSA levels.Â \n\nProstate specific antigen (PSA) is a protein that is used as a marker for the disease â€“ higher levels are associated with a higher risk of prostate cancer.Â  A special mouse model was used for hormone-sensitive prostate cancer that is said to closely mirror the disease in humans. The mice were divided into two groups, one fed a diet 20 percent fat with a healthy one-to-one ratio of omega-6 to omega-3 fatty acids, while the second group of mice was fed the same diet but with the fat derived from mostly omega-6 fatty acids.Â  At the end of the intervention period, the researchers reported that tumour cell growth rates had decreased by 22 per cent and PSA levels by 77 per cent in the group receiving a healthier balance of fatty acids compared with the group that received predominantly omega-6 fatty acids.Â  â€œThis study strongly suggests that eating a healthier ratio of these two types of fatty acids may make a difference in reducing prostate cancer growth, ,â€ said Aronson.\n\nOmega 6 fats are found in corn, safflower and other vegetable oils, nuts, seeds, and red meats. Corn oil is the backbone of the American diet.Â  We consume up to 20 times more omega-6 fatty acids in our diet compared to omega-3 acids,â€ explained Aronson.Â \n\nThe most likely mechanism for the tumour reductions, say the researchers, is the role of metabolites of omega-3 fatty acids, eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA), and the omega-6 acid, arachidonic acid.Â  These three fatty acids compete to be converted by cyclooxgenase enzymes (COX-1 and COX-2) into prostaglandins, which can become either pro-inflammatory and increase tumour growth, or anti-inflammatory and reduce growth.Â  Aronson and his co-workers found that levels of the pro-inflammatory prostaglandin (PGE-2) were 83 per cent lower in tumours in the omega-3 group than in mice on the predominantly omega-6 fatty acid diet.Â  This suggests that higher levels of DHA and EPA may lead to development of more anti-inflammatory prostaglandins.','Improve omega 3 to 6 ratio to protect the prostate','','publish','open','closed','','improve-omega3-to-6-ratio-to-protect-the-prostate','','','2019-10-16 16:00:31','2019-10-16 15:00:31','',0,'http://www.simplyvital.com/blog/?p=659',0,'post','',0),(708,2,'2012-04-17 11:26:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00','For years the pharmaceutical industry has sold us the idea that depression is simply a lack of serotonin in the brain. Sadly this is untrue.\n\nResearch studiesÂ now show that the positive effects of theseÂ SSRI drugs actually occurs viaÂ the dopamine system rather than serotonin.\n\nMore thanÂ 80% of GPs admit to overprescribing anti-depressant drugs, the majority of which fall into this SSRI category. And althouh clinical guidelines state that they should only be used as a short term measure, millions of people take these drugs for years.\n\nThe side efects from raising serotonin levelsÂ artificially high are:\n\nDepression is generally poorly understoodÂ and differentiating betweenÂ real depression andÂ low mood caused byÂ the usualÂ knocks in life that we all suffer on our journey through lifeÂ  is perhaps not easy for a busy GP.','New, natural anti-depressant launched!','','draft','open','closed','','','','','2012-04-17 11:26:39','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://www.simplyvital.com/blog/?p=708',0,'post','',0),(741,2,'2011-04-03 22:12:53','2011-04-03 21:12:53','Antioxidant and pigment supplements are thought to be ineffective for the \"wet\" form of Age Related Macular Degeneration (AMD)Â althoughÂ very helpful for the \"dry\" form.\n\nThat view is now changing .....\n\n<strong>Simply Vital Case Study</strong>\n\nAn elderlyÂ customerÂ was diagnosedÂ with the \"wet\" form of AMDÂ in November 2010. She thenÂ started taking 2 <strong><a href=\"http://www.simplyvital.com/nourish/vitalmacula\">VitalMACULA</a> </strong>capsules daily and when sheÂ attended her follow up appointment at Sunderland eye hospital inÂ February 2011,Â all signsÂ Â of herÂ AMD had disappeared!\n\nHerÂ consultant had expected to see a deterioration in her condition but instead could not find any sign of the disease!\n\nThis is only oneÂ case of course, but it certainly challengesÂ current assumptions about \"wet\" AMD and treatment options.\n\n<strong>Age-related macular degeneration</strong> (AMD) tends to affect people over 50 resulting in loss of vision in the centre of the visual field (the macula) from damage to the retina. Macular degeneration can make it difficult or impossible to read or recognise faces, although enough peripheral vision remains to allow other activities of daily life.\n\nIn the â€œdryâ€ (non-exudative) form, cellular debris known as drusen accumulates behind the retina which can then become detached.\n\nIn the â€œwetâ€ (exudative) form, which is the more severe form, blood vessels grow behind the retina also causing it to become detached. Treatment usually consists of laser coagulation of these vessels or drugs that stop and sometimes reverse blood vessel growth.\n\nThe â€œdryâ€ form of advanced AMD, results from atrophy to the retinal pigment epithelial layer below the retina, which causes vision loss through loss of photoreceptors in the central part of the eye.\n\nNeovascular or exudative AMD, the â€œwetâ€ form of advanced AMD, causes vision loss due to abnormal blood vessel growth leading to blood and protein leakage below the macula and accounts for 10% or so of patients with macular degeneration. Bleeding, leaking, and scarring from these blood vessels eventually causes irreversible damage to the photoreceptors and rapid vision loss if left untreated.\n\n<strong>Treatment options</strong>\n\nNo medical or surgical treatment exists for <strong>â€œdryâ€ AMD</strong>, however experts agree that supplements with high doses of the antioxidants, lutein and zeaxanthin may slow its progression and improve visual acuity.\n\nFor â€œwetâ€ AMD, drugs such as Lucentis (ranibizumab) aimed at preventing the growth of new blood vessels are injected monthly into the eyes.\n\n<strong>Why is VitalMACULA effective against AMD?</strong>\n\n<strong><a title=\"vitalmax\" href=\"http://www.simplyvital.com/nourish-body-and-mind/vitalmax\">VitalMACULA</a> </strong>hasÂ an exceptional array ofÂ nutrients vital for eye health; amino acids, vitamins, minerals andÂ the pigment molecules lutein, zeaxanthin, chlorophyll, carotenesÂ and phycocyanin, so it is likely that this broad and potent spectrum of nutrients and pigments will supportÂ eye health and in the case of this 85 year old lady,Â helped the eye to heal.\n\nWith the variable success rate of the drug (Lucentis) and the side effects experienced which include: discomfort and increased tears in the affected eye(s), itchy or watery eyes, dry eyes, swelling of the eyelids, blurred vision, sinus pain, sore throat, cough, and joint pain, it seems sensible to try the safe option of <strong>VitalMACULA</strong> first.','Age Related Macular Degeneration','','publish','open','closed','','macular-degeneration-responds-to-vitalmax','','','2011-04-03 22:12:53','2011-04-03 21:12:53','',0,'http://www.simplyvital.com/blog/?p=741',0,'post','',0),(750,2,'2012-05-01 12:04:07','0000-00-00 00:00:00','New treatments for Alzheimers disease include the potential use of medium chain triglycerides (MCT oil) or ketone bodies (also called ketoacids) the end product of MCT metabolism. Ketones may not only treat, but also prevent Alzheimerâ€™s disease. MCTs are found in abundance in virgin coconut oil.\n\nIn 2001, Dr. Richard L. Veech of the NIH, and others, published an article entitled, \"Ketone bodies, potential therapeutic uses.\" In 2003, George F. Cahill, Jr. and Richard Veech authored, \"Ketoacids? Good Medicine?\" and in 2004, Richard Veech published a review of the therapeutic implications of ketone bodies.\n\nOur cells can use ketone bodies as an alternative fuel when glucose is not available. Brain cells, specifically neurons, are very limited, more limited than other cells, in what kinds of fuel they can use to function and to stay alive. The body can produce ketone bodies from coconut oil and when on a very low carb diet. Ketones can serve as food for the brain and nervous system in the event that insulin resistance and a lack of glucose availability develops. Providing the ketone bodies appears to protect the brain cells from destruction.\n\nKetones and ketosis haveÂ a bad reputation because of misinformation given during the debate over low carb diets. Dr. Veech has said publicly:\n<blockquote>\"Simply put, ketosis is evolution\'s answer to the thrifty gene. We may have evolved to efficiently store fat for times of famine, says Veech, but we also evolved ketosis to efficiently live off that fat when necessary. Rather than being poison, which is how the press often refers to ketones, they make the body run more efficiently and provide a backup fuel source for the brain. Veech calls ketones \"magic\" and has shown that both the heart and brain run 25 percent more efficiently on ketones than on blood sugar.\"</blockquote>\nIn addition, <strong>one study has shown that ketones trigger a cellular process called chaperone-mediated autophagy (CMA).</strong>\n\nWhat is CMA? It is a cellular process that allows cells to remove junk proteins, organelles, and foreign bodies from the watery interior of the cell and deliver them to the cell\'s waste disposal system for degradation. If this \"junk\" isn\'t removed regularly from the cell\'s interior, it eventually overwhelms and kills the cell.\n\nThis line of ketone research is also yielding answers for Parkinsonâ€™s, Huntingtonâ€™s and other neurodegenerative disorders.\n\nRecent research on Alzheimers disease is revealing that <strong>a diet chronically high in carbohydrates and low in dietary cholesterol is associated with the development of a brain based insulin resistance</strong> (now being called Type 3 Diabetes) which can lead to an imbalance in the cellular function and repair mechanisms of the brain.\n\nThe brain is extremely active metabolically, and it is in a constant state of maintaining a balance between the destructive aspects of burning sugar for energy and rebuilding its neurons (brain cells) from incoming cholesterol molecules.\n\nIf blood cholesterol levels fall too low, and blood sugar is chronically high, this delicate balance is upset, and the destruction of the brain cells begins to take the upper hand as oxidative stress increases.\n\nBecause the affected brain lacks enough cholesterol for rebuilding its neuronal cell walls, it substitutes beta-amyloid substances instead. This leads to the buildup of the amyloid plaques associated with Alzheimers disease. For more information on this theory, see <em><a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/produc